Little stylistic thing that I wanted to suggest. You're using the MC's name a LOT, even in scenes when he's the only one in the action, like the opening paragraphs. Would suggest that you try to cut it back, use a generic pronoun (he, his, etc) when it's not the beginning of a paragraph or try to find a different way to nominate him ("the human" or "the smuggler").

Also, there's a lot of "show, don't tell" changes that you might try to incorporate. For example, the paragraph that starts with "His ship secured by the black armored sith warriors" reads very plainly. It's an exciting scene, he's going to the Sith palace, seeing all of the neat stuff on offer, but we're not getting any sense of how he's reacting to it emotionally. It's just "Farod does X. Farod sees Y. Belokoor does Z." Doesn't really spark the imagination of the reader, it's like instructions for a stage play.

I like the idea of the story, and I'm interested to read more of it, so please don't take this as just shitposting or trying to be a dick. Writefagging is hard and generally thankless work, and I appreciate what you're doing for us!

>what flavor of anthro do you think is best in scifi stories?
Personal tastes, but I like catgirls. There's a lot of room to explore different character archetypes, but there's also a lot stereotypical things you can fall back on (lazy/self-interested, easily bored, like causing mischief, pull the tail when plowing them from behind, etc...)
